<header><h1>Bankruptcy Stops Garnishment</h1><p class="subtitle">How the Automatic Stay Protects Your Paycheck</p></header>
<div class="container"><main id="main-content">
<nav class="breadcrumb-nav" aria-label="Breadcrumb"><a href="https://1328f.org">Home</a><span class="separator">&rsaquo;</span><a href="https://stopgarnishment.org">Bankruptcy Stops Garnishment - How the Automatic Stay Works | stopgarnishment.org</a><span class="separator">&rsaquo;</span><span>Bankruptcy Stops Garnishment</span></nav>

<nav style="margin-bottom:1rem;font-size:.9rem"><a href="/">&larr; Stop Garnishment Home</a></nav>

<div class="content-section"><h2>The Automatic Stay - Immediate Protection</h2>
<p>The moment you file a bankruptcy petition with the court, a powerful federal court order called the "<a href="https://automaticstay.org" title="Automatic Stay in Bankruptcy - Open Bankruptcy Project" target="_blank" rel="noopener">automatic stay</a>" takes effect under 11 U.S.C. 362. This order immediately prohibits all creditors from continuing any collection activity, including <a href="https://garnishedwages.org" title="Wage Garnishment and Bankruptcy - Open Bankruptcy Project" target="_blank" rel="noopener">wage garnishment</a>. Your employer must stop withholding <a href="https://garnishedwages.org" title="Garnished Wages - Open Bankruptcy Project" target="_blank" rel="noopener">garnished wages</a> as soon as they receive notice of the bankruptcy filing.</p>
<p>This protection applies whether you file <a href="https://whatischapter7.com/" title="Chapter 7">Chapter 7</a> or <a href="https://chapter7vs13.org/" title="Chapter 13">Chapter 13</a>. The stay is automatic - you do not need to ask the court for it, and the creditor does not get a chance to object before it takes effect. For more on the <a href="https://automaticstay.org" title="Automatic Stay in Bankruptcy - Open Bankruptcy Project" target="_blank" rel="noopener">automatic stay</a>, visit <a href="https://automaticstay.org">automaticstay.org</a>.</p></div>

<div class="content-section"><h2>Chapter 7 vs. Chapter 13 for Garnishment</h2>
<p>Both chapters stop garnishment immediately, but they work differently long-term. <a href="https://whatischapter7.com/" title="Chapter 7">Chapter 7</a> eliminates most unsecured debts (credit cards, medical bills, personal loans) within about 3-4 months. If the garnishment was for one of these debts, it is permanently eliminated after <a href="https://bankruptcydischarge.org/" title="discharge">discharge</a>. <a href="https://chapter7vs13.org/" title="Chapter 13">Chapter 13</a> reorganizes your debts into a manageable 3-5 year payment plan. The garnishment stops immediately and is replaced by a single monthly plan payment.</p>
<p>Chapter 13 is often the better choice if you need to catch up on mortgage arrears, car payments, or tax debts while keeping the garnishment stopped. Chapter 7 is typically better if you just need to eliminate the underlying debt entirely. Compare the chapters at <a href="https://chapter7vs13.org">chapter7vs13.org</a>.</p></div>

<div class="content-section"><h2>Recovering Garnished Wages</h2>
<p>Under certain circumstances, wages garnished before you filed bankruptcy may be recoverable. Section 547 of the Bankruptcy Code allows the trustee (or debtor) to recover "preference payments" made to creditors within 90 days before filing. If a significant amount was garnished from your wages in the 90 days before your bankruptcy filing, those funds may be clawed back and returned to the <a href="https://1328f.com/glossary.html#estate" title="estate">bankruptcy estate</a>.</p>
<p>This is one reason why timing matters when filing bankruptcy to stop garnishment. If you have been garnished for several months, filing sooner rather than later not only stops future garnishment but may also allow recovery of recently garnished funds.</p></div>

<div class="content-section"><h2>What Garnishment Types Bankruptcy Cannot Stop</h2>
<p>The <a href="https://automaticstay.org" title="Automatic Stay in Bankruptcy - Open Bankruptcy Project" target="_blank" rel="noopener">automatic stay</a> does not stop all types of garnishment. Exceptions include:</p>
<ul><li><strong>Child support and alimony:</strong> Domestic support obligations continue during bankruptcy</li><li><strong>Criminal restitution:</strong> Court-ordered restitution in criminal cases is not stayed</li><li><strong>Tax levies in some circumstances:</strong> The IRS may continue certain tax collection in some cases</li></ul>
<p>For debts that bankruptcy cannot stop, you may need to negotiate directly with the creditor or seek a court modification of the support or restitution order.</p></div>

<div class="content-section"><h2>Emergency Filing to Stop Garnishment</h2>
<p>If garnishment is happening right now and you need it stopped immediately, a "bare bones" or emergency bankruptcy filing may be appropriate. This involves filing the petition with minimal paperwork to trigger the <a href="https://automaticstay.org" title="Automatic Stay in Bankruptcy - Open Bankruptcy Project" target="_blank" rel="noopener">automatic stay</a>, then completing the remaining schedules within 14 days. This is a legitimate legal strategy used specifically when creditors are about to seize assets or wages.</p>
<p>Learn more about emergency filings at <a href="https://howtofilebankruptcy.org">howtofilebankruptcy.org</a>.</p></div>

<div class="faq-section"><h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="faq-item"><h3>How fast does bankruptcy stop garnishment?</h3><p>The <a href="https://automaticstay.org" title="Automatic Stay in Bankruptcy - Open Bankruptcy Project" target="_blank" rel="noopener">automatic stay</a> takes effect immediately when the petition is filed. Your employer typically receives notice within 1-3 business days.</p></div>
<div class="faq-item"><h3>Can I get back garnished wages?</h3><p>Wages garnished within 90 days before filing may be recoverable as a preference payment under 11 U.S.C. 547.</p></div>
<div class="faq-item"><h3>Does bankruptcy stop child support garnishment?</h3><p>No. Domestic support obligations are excepted from the <a href="https://automaticstay.org/" title="automatic stay">automatic stay</a> under 11 U.S.C. 362(b)(2).</p></div>
<div class="faq-item"><h3>Which chapter is better for stopping garnishment?</h3><p>Both stop garnishment immediately. Chapter 7 eliminates the underlying debt in 3-4 months. Chapter 13 restructures it over 3-5 years.</p></div></div>

<div class="cta-box"><p>Check your bankruptcy <a href="https://bankruptcydischarge.org/" title="discharge">discharge</a> eligibility with our free screening tool.</p><a href="https://1328f.com?utm_source=stopgarnishment.org&utm_medium=referral&utm_campaign=btn-network" class="btn">Free Discharge Screener</a></div>
<div class="about-data"><strong>About This Data:</strong> Content based on 11 U.S.C. 362 and 547. Educational content, not legal advice.</div>
</main></div>

